there are two symmetric , finite - bias majorana peaks at rather than a single zero - bias peak , ( b ) the conductance peak is strongly asymmetric with a discontinuous step at the threshold , and ( c ) the width of the peak is set by with its sublinear dependence on junction transparency . the threshold discontinuity in the conductance persists even when including the contributions of the quasiparticle continuum in the substrate green function . to see this , we model the substrate superconductor by a nambu green function . for a topological substrate , this
is appropriate for perfect spin polarization ( spinless -wave superconductor ) . including the tunnel coupling to the tip through the self energy as given above , the substrate green function becomes ^{-1}$ ] . we first focus on the vicinity of the bound state where the conductance is dominated by andreev reflections from the bound state . by straightforward calculation and expansion of in @xcite , we find this differs from the pure bound - state contribution by the additional term in the denominator which involves the determinant ( in particle - hole space ) of the bare substrate
green function . while the determinant of the bound - state contribution to the green function vanishes , this is no longer the case when including the quasiparticle continuum . at subgap energies away from bound states , the green function is a hermitian matrix , so that and hence are real . thus , we find for a majorana state , the real part of the resonance denominator must vanish exactly at . indeed , particle - hole symmetry further constrains to be an even function of which can be approximated as a constant at small ( see @xcite
