resonance@xcite . another type of efimov resonances@xcite is found at positive values of for collisions between a free atom and a dimer , when efimov states intersect with the dimer - atom threshold . while the latter type of efimov resonances corresponds to feshbach resonances in collisions between atoms and dimers@xcite , triatomic efimov resonances can be interpreted as a three - body generalization to feshbach resonances@xcite . striking manifestations of efimov physics have been predicted for three - body recombination processes in ultracold gases with tunable two - body interactions@xcite . three - body recombination leads to losses from
a trapped gas with a rate proportional to the third power of the atomic number density . these losses are commonly described@xcite in terms of a loss rate coefficient . in the resonant case ( ) , it is convenient to express this coefficient in the form , separating a general -scaling@xcite from an additional dependence@xcite . efimov physics is reflected in a logarithmically periodic behavior , corresponding to the scaling of the infinite series of weakly bound trimer states . for negative scattering lengths , the resonant coupling of three atoms to an efimov state opens up fast decay
